2 Simple Linear Regression

names(Boston)
##  [1] "crim"    "zn"      "indus"   "chas"    "nox"     "rm"      "age"    
##  [8] "dis"     "rad"     "tax"     "ptratio" "black"   "lstat"   "medv"

medv(median house value) for neighborhoods around Boston

rm: avg # of rooms/house

age: avg age of house

lstat: % of households with low socioeconomic status

lm(): linear regression model

e.g.lm(y~x,data)

y is response, x is the predictor

lm.fit=lm(medv~lstat,data = Boston)

show regression outcome

lm.fit
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = medv ~ lstat, data = Boston)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)        lstat  
##       34.55        -0.95

predict(): given x(predictors), produce predictions of y(response)

confidence interval

predict(lm.fit,data.frame(lstat=(c(5,10,15))), interval="confidence")
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 29.80359 29.00741 30.59978
## 2 25.05335 24.47413 25.63256
## 3 20.30310 19.73159 20.87461

#plot abline(a,b): add a line with intercept a and slope b

plot(Boston$lstat,Boston$medv)
abline(lm.fit)

lwd= line width, col= color

plot(Boston$lstat,Boston$medv)
abline(lm.fit,lwd=3)

plot(Boston$lstat,Boston$medv)
abline(lm.fit,lwd=3,col="red")

for plot, change color and style

plot(Boston$lstat,Boston$medv,col="red")

plot(Boston$lstat,Boston$medv,pch=20)

plot(Boston$lstat,Boston$medv,pch="+")

plot(1:20,1:20,pch=1:20)

diagnostic plots

apply plot() directly to the output from lm()

plot(lm.fit)

there are 4 plots, we can use par() to devide the plotting region

par(mfrow=c(2,2)) #devide the screen into 2by2 panels
plot(lm.fit)

plot the first one by

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
plot(predict(lm.fit), residuals(lm.fit))

plot the studentized residuals

plot(predict(lm.fit), rstudent(lm.fit))

studentized residual is residual adjusted by RSE and leverage

indicating outliers

produce the leverage statistics: hatvalues()

plot(hatvalues(lm.fit))

identify the index with the largest leverage

which.max(hatvalues(lm.fit))
## 375 
## 375

4 Non-linear Transformations of the Predictors

if we want include some non-linear transformation terms, lm() still works

add I(X^2) to include a quadratic term

I() is used to wrapping things in brackets as a term

lm.fit2=lm(medv~lstat+I(lstat^2),data = Boston)
summary(lm.fit2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = medv ~ lstat + I(lstat^2), data = Boston)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -15.2834  -3.8313  -0.5295   2.3095  25.4148 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 42.862007   0.872084   49.15   <2e-16 ***
## lstat       -2.332821   0.123803  -18.84   <2e-16 ***
## I(lstat^2)   0.043547   0.003745   11.63   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.524 on 503 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.6407, Adjusted R-squared:  0.6393 
## F-statistic: 448.5 on 2 and 503 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

the p-value of the quadratic term shows the model is improved

compare two models

lm.fit=lm(medv~lstat,data = Boston)
lm.fit
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = medv ~ lstat, data = Boston)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)        lstat  
##       34.55        -0.95

Model 2 has one more predictor (the quadratic term)

H0: two models are equally well

H1: model 2 is superior

anova(lm.fit,lm.fit2)

F statistics is 135, p value is near 0, reject H0

we can include a cubic term by adding I(X^3)

for simplicity, we can use poly() to creat polynomial

lm.fit5=lm(medv~poly(lstat,5),data = Boston)
summary(lm.fit5)
##

p-values suggest that including additional polynomial terms, up to 5th order, leads to an improvement

try 6th and higher order

5 Qualitative Predictors

examine Carseats data

names(Carseats)
##  [1] "Sales"       "CompPrice"   "Income"      "Advertising" "Population" 
##  [6] "Price"       "ShelveLoc"   "Age"         "Education"   "Urban"      
## [11] "US"

this dataset includes qualitative predictors such as Shelveloc Shelveloc is the quality of shelving location

summary(Carseats$ShelveLoc)
##    Bad   Good Medium 
##     96     85    219

when we include such categorical variables into lm R generates dummy variables automatically

fit such a regression model:

lm.fit=lm(Sales~.+Income:Advertising+Price:Age,data=Carseats)
